{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3752516,"name":"pryland","username":"pryland","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/pryland/{size}/131208_2.png","created_at":"2025-09-30T19:56:55.132Z","cooked":"<p>So our coral mechanism (Ace)  has an issue.</p>
<p>We  run it DutyCycleOut for intaking coral.</p>
<p>And then we adjust the position of the coral using a PositionDutyCycle to</p>
<p>move it (Motor rotations) <strong>5.0 forward via offset</strong>.</p>
<p>Works fine until the encoder hits 8196 or higher. (a long practice session  +20 cycles )</p>
<p>When this happens and we add 5.0, the SetPos() will run backwards until the encoder gets to 8196.</p>
<p>Have confirmed this repeatedly.  if the encoder is at 9000 and we use the SetPos() it will run backwards until it gets to 8196</p>
<p>This is on a Kraken x44 and TunerX is being used to read the position.</p>
<p>And the magic # is 8196 not 8192</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">
ace = new TalonFX(37, "Canivore2");
    motorPosRequest = new PositionDutyCycle(0);
    motorSpdRequest = new DutyCycleOut(0);

public double getPos() {
    return ace.getPosition().getValueAsDouble();
  }

  public void setPos(double offset) {
    requestedPosition = getPos() + offset;
    ace.setControl(motorPosRequest.withPosition(requestedPosition));

    if (debug) {
      SmartDashboard.putNumber("ACE Current Pos", getPos());
      SmartDashboard.putNumber("ACE Target Pos", requestedPosition);
    }
  }
