<p>What you’re seeing is the maximum setpoint that is possible with a Position based control mode. Typically, mechanisms never achieve more than 8000 rotations especially within an <span class="abbreviation">FRC<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="FIRST Robotics Competition"></template></span> match, so it’s unlikely you’ll see this, but it’s possible with mechanisms such as an intake after extended periods of time such as during practice. In these scenarios, we typically recommend re-setting the position while the robot is disabled to reduce the likelihood of getting to the maximum setpoint while enabled.</p>
<p>Alternatively, you can make use of the “<a href="https://api.ctr-electronics.com/phoenix6/release/java/com/ctre/phoenix6/configs/HardwareLimitSwitchConfigs.html#ForwardLimitAutosetPositionEnable" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">AutoSetPositionOnLimit</a>” configs to set the position to 0 on reverse limit, and manually assert the “<a href="https://api.ctr-electronics.com/phoenix6/release/java/com/ctre/phoenix6/controls/DutyCycleOut.html#LimitReverseMotion" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">LimitReverseMotion</a>” parameter of your intake request to constantly set the position to 0 during intake. Then your normal target would just be 5 rotations.</p>
<h1><a name="p-3752544-example-diagram-1" class="anchor" href="#p-3752544-example-diagram-1"></a>Example Diagram</h1>
